'''Marse Callaway''' (born 1888) known as (Mr. [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) was a black political boss and founder of the Baltimore Police Training School, a black [[policeman]]'s training academy in 1937.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title="Governor Helps Bury 'Mr. GOP': 400 Others Attend Calloway Funeral"|last=|first=|date=May 31, 1952| pages= 1-2.|work=The Baltimore Afro-American|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=CALLAWAY, GOP LEADER, DEAD: Fought For Negro Representation In Political Posts|last=|first=|date=May 20, 1952, p. 18.|work=The Baltimore Sun|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> He was elected as the President of an organization{{which|date=March 2017}} which aimed to bring together Republican [[Voting|voters]], improve voter registration rates especially for the Republican party and to ensure the wellbeing of black people overall.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}
Callaway was a [[real estate]] broker and an influential figure in Republican Politics in Maryland. In 1923 when he became president of the [[Baltimore]] Republican Party. In 1935, Callaway led a lobbying effort to persuade the Maryland legislature to study the question of whether to make the historically black Morgan College a state institution. A legislative commission ended up making a recommendation in favor of transferring Morgan to the state of Maryland, a move that was finalized in 1937.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marse Callaway: A Master Politician|last=Levin|first=Harry|date=February 8, 1958, p. A5|work=The Baltimore Afro-American|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> He organised [[Theodore McKeldin]]'s 1950 campaign for the position of Mayor of Baltimore.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} He was recognized at a meeting of over 1500 people at the Bethel AME Church in Baltimore in 1939 for his work.
Later in his life{{when|date=March 2017}}, Marse was charged with eight counts of receiving money under false pretenses and one count of failing to pay a former employee seven weeks wages.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} Twelve further charges of larceny after trust of funds paid by persons as deposits on pieces of property were added to the indictment to which he pleaded guilty. He was sentenced to a three-year [[suspended sentence]] and when summing up Judge Robert France asserted that Callaway had been "a respected and outstanding citizen in his own community and the city of Baltimore". Callaway was also ordered to pay restitution.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}
Marse Callaway died on May 19, 1952 at [[Provident Hospital (Baltimore)|Provident Hospital]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://search.proquest.com.proxy-ub.researchport.umd.edu/docview/541793702?accountid=28969|title=Callaway, GOP Leader, Dead|last=|first=|date=May 20, 1952|work=The Baltimore Sun|access-date=February 21, 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
